            AppRoutes = """["/payables"]""",
            Tags = """["payables","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Payables — Advanced Reference\n\nEdge-case and power-user notes for Accounts Payable. For the day-to-day flow (entering bills, recording payments, the bill lifecycle) start with the Payables Overview, Field Reference, and Walkthrough. This page collects the extra details those modules leave out.\n\n## Multi-Currency Bills & Settlement Exchange Rates\n\nOn a single-currency install none of this is visible — the **Currency** and **FX Rate** fields are hidden, and every amount is in your default currency. This surface appears only when more than one currency is set up.\n\n- A bill has a currency and an **exchange rate** that converts the bill total to your books' currency, using the rate on the bill date. If you leave the currency blank, the bill uses your books' currency at a rate of 1. The rate must be greater than zero.\n- Each **payment you apply** carries its own **settlement exchange rate** — the rate on the day you pay, which usually differs from the rate on the bill. The gap between the two is the **exchange gain or loss** on that payment. It is figured per bill you pay, not per payment.\n- Because the gain or loss is figured per bill, one payment that settles several foreign-currency bills can land a different gain or loss on each. You enter the rate on the bill and again on each bill you pay; the difference is worked out for you.\n- Bills created from an expense are always in your books' currency at a rate of 1. Expenses do not carry a foreign currency into Payables.\n\n## Transmission Details\n\nElectronic payments (Bank Transfer, Wire) track their handoff to the bank. The payment detail shows the full picture; non-electronic payments leave these blank.\n\n- **Status** — Queued, Retrying, Succeeded, Failed, or Cancelled.\n- **Attempts** — how many times a send has been tried; shown next to the Retrying label.\n- **Next attempt** — when the next automatic retry is scheduled, while it is retrying.\n- **Last error** — the most recent reason a send failed, shown on a failed payment so you can follow up.\n- **Confirmation reference** — the bank's reference, recorded once a send succeeds.\n\nWhen a send fails, a banner appears at the top of both the Bills and Payments tabs, and the bill shows a **Payment Failed** label. There is also a separate admin screen that lists every failed payment in one place, available to Admin, Manager, and Office Manager when payment sending is turned on. **Retry Transmission** tries a failed or cancelled send again; it is refused once a send has already succeeded, because the money has already moved.\n\n## Expenses That Become Bills, and the Void Restriction\n\nAn expense that is settled through a vendor (one that pays Accounts Payable, or simply has a vendor) is **turned into a vendor bill when it is approved**, so it flows through the same Payables machinery — it ages, it is paid by ordinary vendor payments, and it books the right accounting entry. Expenses paid in cash, with no vendor, or for zero or less are not turned into bills; they keep the older expense path.\n\n- This requires the Payables billing feature to be turned on. When it is off, the older expense path handles it instead.\n- A bill made this way is **born Approved** — approving the expense is what approves the bill, so it does not go through a separate Draft-to-Approved step. It remembers the expense it came from and shows a **From Expense** label in the list.\n- **One live bill per expense:** at most one active bill can exist for an expense. Re-approving returns the existing bill rather than making a duplicate.\n- **Void restriction:** a From-Expense bill **cannot be voided here** — its life follows the expense. Voiding it directly would leave the expense approved with its bill quietly gone. To undo it, **reject the expense or ask for a revision**; that voids the bill and reverses its accounting entry together.\n- Undoing it this way is **blocked when payments have been applied**, because the payment would point at a bill that no longer exists. Void the payment or payments first. This is the same rule that applies to voiding ordinary bills.\n\n## Accounting-Provider Boundary\n\nPayables is an **accounting-bounded** feature: it owns Accounts Payable only in **standalone mode**, when no outside accounting provider is connected. When an outside provider such as QuickBooks or Xero is connected, Accounts Payable is managed there instead, and the built-in module steps back rather than keeping duplicate bills and payments.\n\n- Full general-ledger posting of bills and payments is an aspirational feature that is not switched on today. While it is off, approving a bill still moves it forward for everyday work — it is payable, it ages, and it can be paid — but it does not write a journal entry yet. All the everyday effects (status changes, three-way-match tracking, restoring purchase-order quantities when a bill is voided) work either way.\n- The **Accounts** and **Batches** tabs (vendor bank accounts and NACHA payment batches) are a separate feature that stays hidden unless an administrator turns it on. See the dedicated Bank Accounts and Payment Batches modules.","sections":[]}"""
